See below for instructions on configuring specific parameter types. Numeric bounds are defined using
mathematical set symbols.
<h2>Increasing/Decreasing/Range</h2>
Parameter trends in the specified direction, or stays without the specified range.
<pre>```{
    "type": "Increasing",
    "definition": {
        "valid_range": "[700,1000]",
        "monitor": "[850,900)",
        "alarm": "[700,850]",
        ...
    }
}```</pre><h2>Binary</h2>
Parameters that are either true or false.
<pre>```{
    "type": "Binary",
    "definition": {
        "alarm": "true"
    }
}```</pre><h2>Trend</h2>
Calculates the gradient value for a given set of data up to the last maintenance date on a particular component.
Requires the trend_parameter field to be set. trend_min_samples can be set if a minimum amount of data should
be derived before the gradient can be calculated. The settings for alarm, monitor, valid are identical to
Increasing, Decreasing and Range parameters.
            
<h3>Without subname</h3><pre>```{
    "type": "Trend",
    "definition": {
        "trend_parameter": "Diameter",
        "trend_min_samples": 30,
        ...
    }
}```</pre><h3>With subname e.g. Groove1 WidthMM</h3><pre>```{
    "type": "Trend",
    "definition": {
        "trend_parameter": "Groove1.WidthMM",
        "trend_min_samples": 30,
        ...
    }
}```</pre><h2>RMS</h2>
Calculates the root mean square for a given set of data up to the last maintenance date on a particular
component. Requires the trend_parameter field to be set. trend_min_samples can be set if a minimum amount of
data should be derived before the gradient can be calculated. The settings for alarm, monitor, valid are
identical to Increasing, Decreasing and Range parameters.
            
<h3>Without subname</h3><pre>```{
    "type": "RMS",
    "definition": {
        "trend_parameter": "Diameter",
        "trend_min_samples": 30,
        ...
    }
}```</pre><h3>With subname e.g. Groove1 WidthMM</h3><pre>```{
    "type": "RMS",
    "definition": {
        "trend_parameter": "Groove1.WidthMM",
        "trend_min_samples": 30,
        ...
    }
}```</pre><h2>Mean</h2>
Calculates the mean/average value for a given set of data up to the last maintenance date on a particular
component. Requires the trend_parameter field to be set. trend_min_samples can be set if a minimum amount of
data should be derived before the gradient can be calculated. The settings for alarm, monitor, valid are
identical to Increasing, Decreasing and Range parameters.
            
<h3>Without subname</h3><pre>```{
    "type": "Mean",
    "definition": {
        "trend_parameter": "Diameter",
        "trend_min_samples": 30,
        ...
    }
}```</pre><h3>With subname e.g. Groove1 WidthMM</h3><pre>```{
    "type": "Mean",
    "definition": {
        "trend_parameter": "Groove1.WidthMM",
        "trend_min_samples": 30,
        ...
    }
}```</pre><h2>Difference</h2>
Calculates the difference between two or more values (as listed in related_parameters) in a given measurement,
at this time, the values must be present on the same component/feature for it to be calculated successfully.
The settings for alarm, monitor, valid are identical to Increasing, Decreasing and Range parameters.
            
<h3>Without subname</h3><pre>```{
    "type": "Difference",
    "definition": {
        "related_parameter": ["Diameter","Height"],
        ...
    }
}```</pre><h3>With subname e.g. Groove1 WidthMM</h3><pre>```{
    "type": "Difference",
    "definition": {
        "related_parameter": ["Groove1.WidthMM", "Groove2.WidthMM"],
        ...
    }
}```</pre><h2>Percentile Range</h2>
Calculates the configured value for a given set of data up to the last maintenance date on a particular
component. Requires the trend_parameter field to be set. trend_min_samples can be set if a minimum amount of
data should be derived before the gradient can be calculated. A value must be set for the percentile field
indicating which percentile between 0-100 is being calculated. The settings for alarm, monitor, valid are
identical to Increasing, Decreasing and Range parameters.
            
<h3>Without subname</h3><pre>```{
    "type": "PercentileRange",
    "definition": {
        "trend_parameter": "Diameter",
        "trend_min_samples": 30,
        "percentile": 10,
        ...
    }
}```</pre><h3>With subname e.g. Groove1 WidthMM</h3><pre>```{
    "type": "PercentileRange",
    "definition": {
        "trend_parameter": "Groove1.WidthMM",
        "trend_min_samples": 30,
        "percentile": 90,
        ...
    }
}```</pre><h2>Array of Increasing/Decreasing/Range</h2>
Result from backend arrives as an array, this result is not derived. The settings for alarm, monitor, valid
are identical to Increasing, Decreasing and Range parameters. The settings are applied to each value in the
array when they arrive.
            
<pre>```{
    "type": "ArrayOfIncreasing",
    "definition": {
        ...
    }
}```</pre><h2>Array of Binary</h2>
Result from backend arrives as an array, this result is not derived. The settings for alarm, monitor, valid
are identical to Binary parameters. The settings are applied to each value in the array when they arrive.
            
<pre>```{
    "type": "ArrayOfIncreasing",
    "definition": {
        ...
    }
}```</pre><h2>Array Length</h2>
Calculates the length of an array given the related parameter. Requires the related_parameter field to be
set. If multiple related parameters are set, we calculate the total length of all related arrays. The settings
for alarm, monitor, valid are identical to Increasing, Decreasing and Range parameters.
            
<h3>Without subname</h3><pre>```{
    "type": "ArrayLength",
    "definition": {
        "related_parameter": ["LugNutAngles"],
        ...
    }
}```</pre><h3>With subname e.g. Groove1 WidthMM</h3><pre>```{
    "type": "ArrayLength",
    "definition": {
        "related_parameter": ["Lug1.LugNutAngles"],
        ...
    }
}```</pre>

